1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:00,940
Speaker 8: Hi, everyone.

2
00:00:01,180 --> 00:00:01,960
I'm Ritwik Pandya.

3
00:00:02,280 --> 00:00:06,060
I manage engineering teams focused
on large-scale payment platform at

4
00:00:06,120 --> 00:00:07,620
the leading financial institution.

5
00:00:08,380 --> 00:00:10,730
Today, I want to talk about
the problem many of us have

6
00:00:10,740 --> 00:00:12,070
seen in the production systems.

7
00:00:12,740 --> 00:00:16,760
There is sudden p99 latency spike
during the peak hours, where the

8
00:00:16,799 --> 00:00:18,600
response times jumps nearly four-fold.

9
00:00:19,100 --> 00:00:21,960
I'll walk you through a single
architectural shift around the

10
00:00:21,980 --> 00:00:26,620
deterministic routing and the data
locality, which significantly can improve

11
00:00:26,660 --> 00:00:31,259
the system behavior, delivering higher
throughput and reducing the tail latency

12
00:00:31,299 --> 00:00:36,089
by, say, fourteen-- fifty-nine percent,
which we saw, all on the same hardware

13
00:00:36,100 --> 00:00:38,290
and the same database infrastructure.

14
00:00:38,790 --> 00:00:39,890
So here's the story.

15
00:00:40,650 --> 00:00:44,538
Our base p99 latency was around
twelve milliseconds, and during the

16
00:00:44,550 --> 00:00:48,730
peak hours, it jumped to forty-seven
milliseconds, nearly four times slower.

17
00:00:49,230 --> 00:00:52,600
Transactions started timing out,
clients retried automatically.

18
00:00:52,879 --> 00:00:56,980
Retry piled up on top of the
existing load, and very quickly, we

19
00:00:57,019 --> 00:00:58,820
were dealing with the retry storm.

20
00:00:59,180 --> 00:01:02,219
The SLA alert fired, pagers went off.

21
00:01:02,739 --> 00:01:08,579
At first, it was obvious answer to be
that, "Hey, add more nodes." So we did.

22
00:01:09,079 --> 00:01:10,339
But latency didn't improve.

23
00:01:10,859 --> 00:01:12,578
In fact, it got slightly worse.

24
00:01:13,259 --> 00:01:14,419
That was the key insight.

25
00:01:14,499 --> 00:01:18,079
The problem wasn't the capacity,
the problem was the coordination

26
00:01:18,119 --> 00:01:19,759
overhead caused by the randomness.

27
00:01:20,259 --> 00:01:25,159
Every request was l-landing on
the random node, while the actual

28
00:01:25,219 --> 00:01:27,119
data often lived somewhere else.

29
00:01:27,879 --> 00:01:32,079
So each transaction triggered the
extra coordination, cross-node

30
00:01:32,199 --> 00:01:36,899
lookups, replication waits,
log checks, cache misses.

31
00:01:37,399 --> 00:01:41,459
The system was spending more
time cor- coordinating the work

32
00:01:41,959 --> 00:01:43,139
than actually doing the work.

33
00:01:44,019 --> 00:01:47,179
Think of it like a hospital where
every patient is assigned to

34
00:01:47,239 --> 00:01:50,299
the random doctor on each visit.

35
00:01:51,039 --> 00:01:55,659
The doctor doesn't have your record
locally, so they first fetch the

36
00:01:55,699 --> 00:02:00,299
files, call the departments, verify the
context, and then begin the treatment.

37
00:02:01,079 --> 00:02:04,679
That's effectively what our
database was doing under the load.

38
00:02:05,600 --> 00:02:10,600
So we ask a simple question: What
if every transaction could land to

39
00:02:10,679 --> 00:02:14,160
the node that already has its data?

40
00:02:14,660 --> 00:02:18,660
So before getting in the solution,
it's worth grounding this why

41
00:02:18,760 --> 00:02:20,640
the latency actually matters.

42
00:02:21,380 --> 00:02:25,660
In transactional systems, latency
isn't the performance metrics.

43
00:02:25,881 --> 00:02:28,960
It's directly translate
into the business impact.

44
00:02:29,899 --> 00:02:33,660
There was a well-known pattern across
the industry, and Amazon reported that

45
00:02:33,799 --> 00:02:38,040
every additional hundred millisecond
of the latency impacted revenue.

46
00:02:38,859 --> 00:02:44,560
Google observed measurable query drop-offs
with the few hundred millisecond delay.

47
00:02:45,060 --> 00:02:49,460
Same goes with other top industry vendors.

48
00:02:49,960 --> 00:02:52,021
We saw the same effect operationally.

49
00:02:52,362 --> 00:02:56,660
When our P99 climbed up from
twelve millisecond to forty-seven

50
00:02:56,780 --> 00:03:02,761
millisecond under the peak load,
about three point two requests,

51
00:03:02,841 --> 00:03:04,620
percent requests began timing out.

52
00:03:05,421 --> 00:03:12,160
And every failed transaction had a real
downstream cost: retries, operational

53
00:03:12,241 --> 00:03:15,362
overhead, customer friction, SLA exposure.

54
00:03:16,261 --> 00:03:19,501
At our scale, even the few
percentage points become

55
00:03:19,561 --> 00:03:22,900
materially expensive very quickly.

56
00:03:23,400 --> 00:03:29,680
At same time, the business was focusing
nearly twice transaction growth over

57
00:03:29,700 --> 00:03:33,220
the next year, but the infrastructure
budget wasn't doubling with it.

58
00:03:33,740 --> 00:03:38,081
So simply scaling horizon-
horizontally by adding more nodes

59
00:03:38,160 --> 00:03:39,700
wasn't a sustainable answer.

60
00:03:40,200 --> 00:03:43,840
That constraint focused us to
rethink architecture itself,

61
00:03:44,460 --> 00:03:46,361
not just add more hardware.

62
00:03:46,861 --> 00:03:50,400
So this was our baseline
architecture where we started.

63
00:03:50,680 --> 00:03:54,380
A client request hits to load
balancer, and the load balancer

64
00:03:54,480 --> 00:03:56,881
selects an application node randomly.

65
00:03:57,360 --> 00:03:59,100
Let's say node one.

66
00:03:59,600 --> 00:04:03,501
But the data for the transaction
may actually owned by node three.

67
00:04:03,801 --> 00:04:08,900
So node one now has locate the correct
range of leaseholder, coordinate

68
00:04:09,001 --> 00:04:14,821
across the nodes, wait for replication
acknowledgment, acquire locks, and only

69
00:04:14,881 --> 00:04:17,061
then execute the transac-transaction.

70
00:04:17,941 --> 00:04:21,331
Every additional network hop adds latency.

71
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:27,821
Every coordination boundary introduce
the queu-queuing and contention.

72
00:04:28,601 --> 00:04:31,601
Over the time, four major
problem become obvious.

73
00:04:32,101 --> 00:04:37,041
First, every request effectively
rediscover data locally from the scratch.

74
00:04:37,541 --> 00:04:42,061
The request path had no awareness
where data already lived.

75
00:04:42,561 --> 00:04:48,480
Second, writes triggered synchronously,
cross-node coordination happens.

76
00:04:49,360 --> 00:04:53,900
Transactions spend significant time
waiting for-- waiting on replication

77
00:04:53,940 --> 00:04:58,100
and consensus na- overhead rather
than doing the useful work.

78
00:04:58,600 --> 00:05:00,780
Third, utilization become uneven.

79
00:05:01,280 --> 00:05:05,661
Some nodes saturated while
other remained underutilized.

80
00:05:06,661 --> 00:05:10,941
We were paying for the cluster capacity
we couldn't ef- efficiently consume.

81
00:05:11,441 --> 00:05:16,661
And the fourth one, under the
peak concurrency, lock contention

82
00:05:16,701 --> 00:05:18,401
become increasingly visible.

83
00:05:19,121 --> 00:05:25,061
The queue depth grew, retries increased,
and the tail latency amplified rapidly.

84
00:05:25,561 --> 00:05:29,101
This is actually a default behavior
of many distribus- distributed

85
00:05:29,181 --> 00:05:31,161
systems under the random routing.

86
00:05:31,661 --> 00:05:38,021
A moderated load, it works reasonably
well, but as concurrency increases,

87
00:05:38,641 --> 00:05:42,321
the coordination overhead starts
dominating the request path

88
00:05:42,821 --> 00:05:46,841
We tried to instrumentate the
entire request path under-- and to

89
00:05:46,881 --> 00:05:51,641
understand where those forty-seven
milliseconds were actually going.

90
00:05:52,141 --> 00:05:54,571
And the result were honestly surprising.

91
00:05:54,651 --> 00:05:59,151
Around twelve milliseconds were
spent just re-resolving metadata

92
00:05:59,191 --> 00:06:00,991
and determining where data lived.

93
00:06:01,491 --> 00:06:06,011
Another eighteen millisecond went
into cross-node coordination,

94
00:06:06,091 --> 00:06:07,951
replication, acknowledgments, et cetera.

95
00:06:08,451 --> 00:06:13,311
Lock contention contributed roughly
eight millisecond under concurrency.

96
00:06:14,071 --> 00:06:17,571
Connection management and
network overhead added ano-

97
00:06:18,331 --> 00:06:20,121
other another four milliseconds.

98
00:06:20,621 --> 00:06:26,021
So when we added everything up the
real insight became o- obvious.

99
00:06:26,261 --> 00:06:30,061
The most of the latency wasn't the
computation, it was coordination.

100
00:06:30,561 --> 00:06:37,061
The system was spending majority of its
time locating the data, synchronizing

101
00:06:37,101 --> 00:06:40,841
the state, waiting for locks, and
coordinating across the nodes.

102
00:06:41,341 --> 00:06:46,841
Only small fraction of the request
path was actual transaction execution.

103
00:06:47,451 --> 00:06:52,161
A useful analogy is say, a restaurant
where the kitchen spend nearly all

104
00:06:52,221 --> 00:06:57,441
of its time coordinating the orders,
locating in-ingredients, and handling

105
00:06:57,561 --> 00:07:04,321
work between the stations, and only tiny
portion of actual-- actually cooking food.

106
00:07:04,821 --> 00:07:07,561
At some point, adding
more cooks doesn't help.

107
00:07:08,061 --> 00:07:13,181
The operational overhead itself
becomes the bottleneck, and that was

108
00:07:13,221 --> 00:07:15,221
the architectural realization for us.

109
00:07:15,721 --> 00:07:17,841
We didn't need bigger system.

110
00:07:17,901 --> 00:07:20,541
We needed system to coordinate less.

111
00:07:21,041 --> 00:07:25,181
And just to be precise, these
numbers are the representative

112
00:07:25,841 --> 00:07:31,101
attribution from the distributed
tracing and span-level analysis.

113
00:07:31,601 --> 00:07:36,660
Percentage decomposition is never the
mathematically perfect in the practice,

114
00:07:37,160 --> 00:07:42,380
but the proposition were consistent
and reproducible across the runs.

115
00:07:42,880 --> 00:07:47,120
That become the turning point of
discussions with the leadership

116
00:07:47,160 --> 00:07:51,520
because the optimization opportunity
was suddenly very visible

117
00:07:52,020 --> 00:07:56,060
Now, one architectural decision
changed everything for us.

118
00:07:56,560 --> 00:08:02,510
Instead of routing transaction randomly,
we started routing each transaction to the

119
00:08:02,660 --> 00:08:06,680
node most likely to already own its data.

120
00:08:07,180 --> 00:08:11,080
Routing decision were deterministic
based on the key hashing, and the

121
00:08:11,160 --> 00:08:18,960
execution was in parallel with isolated
worker pools to avoid shared contention.

122
00:08:19,460 --> 00:08:23,270
That becomes core architecture principle
behind the entire system, and now

123
00:08:23,300 --> 00:08:26,700
underlying idea itself isn't new.

124
00:08:27,650 --> 00:08:32,409
The system like Dynamo introduced the
partition-aware routing years ago,

125
00:08:32,909 --> 00:08:37,549
and later research such as Calvin
explored deterministic transaction

126
00:08:37,669 --> 00:08:39,389
scheduling at the database layer.

127
00:08:39,889 --> 00:08:46,409
What we found interestingly was applying
the same locality principle earlier in

128
00:08:46,449 --> 00:08:51,469
request path and applic-- and at the
application and routing layer itself.

129
00:08:52,130 --> 00:08:57,739
Because once the request arrives near
the correct data from the beginning,

130
00:08:58,270 --> 00:09:03,140
an entire category of coordination
overhead start disappearing.

131
00:09:03,640 --> 00:09:09,020
There will be a fewer metadata lookups,
fewer cross-node hops, better cache

132
00:09:09,080 --> 00:09:12,330
locality, lower lock, lock contention.

133
00:09:13,240 --> 00:09:20,240
So the real gain real gain wasn't about
inventing faster algorithm, it was about

134
00:09:20,280 --> 00:09:26,220
eliminating unnecessary movement of data
and coordinating that never needed to

135
00:09:26,260 --> 00:09:27,900
be happen in the first place itself.

136
00:09:28,400 --> 00:09:35,480
A few quick words on why this approach
works particularly well in the

137
00:09:35,540 --> 00:09:37,380
modern distributed data-databases.

138
00:09:37,880 --> 00:09:44,460
Most distributed databases today already
optimize around the locality internally.

139
00:09:44,960 --> 00:09:50,760
They partition data into ranges and shards
replicate those ranges across the nodes,

140
00:09:50,940 --> 00:09:57,060
and use consensus protocol like Raft to
coordinate ownership and consistency.

141
00:09:57,560 --> 00:10:04,610
The important realization for us was, if
the database is already locality-aware

142
00:10:04,750 --> 00:10:09,030
internally, the application layer
should stop behaving randomly.

143
00:10:09,530 --> 00:10:14,949
Under traditional random routing,
request lands on any random nodes,

144
00:10:15,629 --> 00:10:20,349
and the database spends additional
time forwarding the request,

145
00:10:20,489 --> 00:10:25,030
resolving the ownership, coordinating
replicas, and managing cross-node

146
00:10:25,089 --> 00:10:30,531
communication Solution is deterministic
routing that changes everything.

147
00:10:31,389 --> 00:10:35,388
By routing the request based on
the same partition key used by the

148
00:10:35,468 --> 00:10:40,608
database and application increase the
probability that request arrives near

149
00:10:40,648 --> 00:10:43,509
the node already coordinating that data.

150
00:10:44,009 --> 00:10:49,908
That redu-reduces unnecessary hops,
improves cache locality, lower

151
00:10:49,988 --> 00:10:53,629
coordination overhead, and shorten
the critical transaction path.

152
00:10:54,129 --> 00:10:59,030
The database still hurdles
correctness, replication, failover,

153
00:10:59,469 --> 00:11:01,990
rebalancing, and consensus underneath.

154
00:11:02,390 --> 00:11:04,930
We are not replacing the
distributed coordination here.

155
00:11:05,031 --> 00:11:11,690
We are reducing how often the system needs
expensive coordination on the hot path.

156
00:11:12,609 --> 00:11:18,430
This broader principle shows across many
distributed systems, from the Dynamo-style

157
00:11:18,490 --> 00:11:23,510
partitioning to locality-aware
databases like Spanner, CockroachDB,

158
00:11:23,611 --> 00:11:26,531
You have ByteDB, TiDB, and others.

159
00:11:27,031 --> 00:11:30,231
So how could we actually implement this?

160
00:11:30,351 --> 00:11:34,231
At the conceptual level, the
routing logic is sup-surprisingly

161
00:11:34,471 --> 00:11:36,311
simple and very bookish in a way.

162
00:11:37,211 --> 00:11:43,111
That take your transactions primary
key, hash it, and map that hash

163
00:11:43,210 --> 00:11:45,651
to one of the node in the cluster.

164
00:11:46,330 --> 00:11:46,670
Simple.

165
00:11:47,170 --> 00:11:52,410
And that hash tells the application
which node should handle the request.

166
00:11:52,910 --> 00:11:58,150
So in that way, there is no random
load balancing, no request path

167
00:11:58,250 --> 00:12:02,770
metadata lookup will be there, no
guessing where the data might live.

168
00:12:03,750 --> 00:12:07,540
And because the routing is
deterministic, the same key

169
00:12:07,650 --> 00:12:10,090
consistently lands on the same node.

170
00:12:11,050 --> 00:12:13,949
That consistency is what creates locality.

171
00:12:14,870 --> 00:12:18,530
Now, in production, we don't
actually use naive modulo hashing.

172
00:12:18,630 --> 00:12:24,010
Modulo works fine in examples, but behaves
badly when the cluster membership changes.

173
00:12:24,610 --> 00:12:28,829
For example, if you add or remove a node
and suddenly the most of the keyspace

174
00:12:28,910 --> 00:12:34,470
gets remapped, that creates massive cache
churn and unnecessary redistribution.

175
00:12:34,970 --> 00:12:38,710
So instead, we use consistent
hashing with virtual nodes.

176
00:12:39,370 --> 00:12:44,870
With consistent hashing, when the
node is added or removed, only a

177
00:12:44,950 --> 00:12:46,970
small portion of the keyspace moves.

178
00:12:47,470 --> 00:12:52,550
This is the same foundation idea used
in Akamai, Cloudflare, Dynamo-style

179
00:12:52,650 --> 00:12:55,949
partitioning, and large-scale
distribus-- distributed caches.

180
00:12:56,449 --> 00:12:59,870
Once we introduced the deterministic
routing, the several benefits

181
00:12:59,890 --> 00:13:01,390
started compounding naturally.

182
00:13:02,390 --> 00:13:06,790
Request bitten-- requests become
predictable, metadata resolution

183
00:13:06,890 --> 00:13:12,870
disappeared from the hot path, cache
locality improves because same key

184
00:13:12,910 --> 00:13:17,930
repeatedly hit the same execution path,
and load distribution stayed relatively

185
00:13:17,970 --> 00:13:21,969
balanced because the hashing spread
keys uniformly across the cluster.

186
00:13:22,469 --> 00:13:25,889
One important caveat here
the choice of key matters.

187
00:13:26,389 --> 00:13:33,848
The routing key needs to be stable, high
car-- high cardinality is needed, and

188
00:13:33,888 --> 00:13:36,868
closely aligned with your access pattern.

189
00:13:37,628 --> 00:13:43,718
You don't want to hash on something
mutable, and you definitely

190
00:13:43,809 --> 00:13:47,868
don't want keyspaces with only
handful of possible values.

191
00:13:48,468 --> 00:13:53,849
Otherwise, you simply move the bottleneck
instead of eliminating it so now routing

192
00:13:53,929 --> 00:13:58,969
solved only one part of the problem but
execution was the other half, right?

193
00:13:59,719 --> 00:14:04,729
Because deterministic routing alone
improves the locality, but it-- if

194
00:14:04,929 --> 00:14:10,669
all requests still execute through the
shared execution path, connection simply

195
00:14:10,769 --> 00:14:13,609
moves somewhere else in the system.

196
00:14:14,289 --> 00:14:18,509
So we paired deterministic routing
with thread-to-node affinity.

197
00:14:19,489 --> 00:14:22,369
So this is second fold
of the solution here.

198
00:14:23,269 --> 00:14:28,429
Say thread zero primarily handled
work for node zero, thread

199
00:14:28,509 --> 00:14:30,529
one for node one, and so on.

200
00:14:31,169 --> 00:14:34,529
Each worker thread own its
own dedicated connection pool

201
00:14:34,949 --> 00:14:36,589
to its assigned node group.

202
00:14:37,349 --> 00:14:42,309
No shared pools, no cross-threaded
coordination during the connection

203
00:14:42,369 --> 00:14:49,809
ac-acquisition, no l-lock contention
around the pooled resources, and this part

204
00:14:49,929 --> 00:14:52,928
mattered more than we initially expected.

205
00:14:53,749 --> 00:14:58,859
Our first implementation actually used
shared connection pool across threads.

206
00:14:59,459 --> 00:15:02,059
Under load, we performed terribly.

207
00:15:02,779 --> 00:15:10,519
Thread spend surprisingly amount of
time containing the pooled connection,

208
00:15:10,779 --> 00:15:14,959
waiting for the synchronization
and fighting each other internally.

209
00:15:15,719 --> 00:15:19,869
In some scenarios, contention
become worse than the original

210
00:15:20,019 --> 00:15:21,199
single-threaded baseline.

211
00:15:21,699 --> 00:15:23,598
Again, the restaurant analogy here.

212
00:15:23,838 --> 00:15:29,398
If every waiter can serve every
table, they constant-- constantly

213
00:15:29,438 --> 00:15:35,118
cross paths, interrupts each other,
and compete for the same space.

214
00:15:35,838 --> 00:15:41,778
But if each waiter owns a dedicated
section, movement become predictable

215
00:15:42,478 --> 00:15:46,228
and collisions largely disappear.

216
00:15:46,308 --> 00:15:49,448
That's effectively what
thread affinity gives us.

217
00:15:49,948 --> 00:15:55,848
The round-robin scheduling kept work even
evenly distributed across the workers.

218
00:15:56,648 --> 00:16:00,348
Asynchronous input/output
prevented threads from the

219
00:16:00,409 --> 00:16:02,508
blocking on the network wa-waits.

220
00:16:03,488 --> 00:16:09,268
Persistent connection eliminated the
repeated setup and teardown cos-cost.

221
00:16:09,768 --> 00:16:14,529
So now let's talk about the operational
side of this Because we are not optimizing

222
00:16:14,569 --> 00:16:20,509
the algorithm here, we are, and in such
systems, we run them on Kubernetes.

223
00:16:21,249 --> 00:16:26,249
In our case, we realized this thing
very rapidly or very quickly that

224
00:16:26,309 --> 00:16:32,589
default Kub- Kubernetes behavior is
often optimized for general availability

225
00:16:32,609 --> 00:16:35,169
and not for the tail latency.

226
00:16:35,879 --> 00:16:42,699
And that's where we tried to-- we took
s- say four configuration decisions here.

227
00:16:43,339 --> 00:16:46,399
One is stateful sets of database layer.

228
00:16:46,489 --> 00:16:51,609
Distributed database rel-rely
heavily on stable network identity

229
00:16:51,649 --> 00:16:56,589
and persistent storage, and that's
where stateful sets help us.

230
00:16:57,069 --> 00:17:02,329
It gives us predictable predictable
pod identities, durable volumes,

231
00:17:02,949 --> 00:17:06,489
and safer rolling updates during
the quorum-sensitive operations.

232
00:17:07,229 --> 00:17:09,689
The second one is node affinity.

233
00:17:09,848 --> 00:17:15,029
So we try to co-locate the
application workloads a- as close

